                                <title2
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545824678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-05-08T10:14:22.135-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Seeing the impact firsthand"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2023-08-11T16:33:26.326-04:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-08-11T16:39:12.534-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="SCHAFSM"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>As the project manager of the Chamas for Change since 2012, Justus E. Ikemeri has seen firsthand the impact on individual mothers and their families. He recalls one group focused on microfinance, in which the members pooled their money and worked together to eventually increase the funds fivefold. Several groups have opened small businesses together, offering an opportunity for both women and their spouses to earn income.&lt;/p>&#xa;&lt;p>“In the microfinance program, everybody shares – you invest in each other,” Ikemeri said. “My vision is to take the program country-wide and then international.”&lt;/p>&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container4_copy_copy>
